# Incident Assistant — Project Rules

You are working on **Incident Assistant**, a Java 21 / Spring Boot 3 AI demo project.

This project must follow **specification-driven development**.

## Core principles

1. Do not implement features before a spec exists.
2. Do not modify code before producing an implementation plan.
3. Do not start phase implementation until that phase is broken into stories (see **Story-based implementation**).
4. Do not expand the current phase scope without human approval.
5. Each phase must be fully tested before the next phase starts; a phase is complete only when all required stories are done and phase acceptance criteria pass.
6. Prefer simple monolith design first; avoid premature microservices.
7. Keep future microservice boundaries in mind through clean modules and interfaces.
8. AI behavior must be safe, testable, and grounded in evidence.
9. The assistant must separate facts, assumptions, and recommendations.
10. RAG answers must cite sources.
11. MCP tools must be explicit, controlled, and testable.
12. No automatic remediation actions in early phases.
13. All external dependencies must be abstracted behind interfaces.
14. All LLM calls must be mockable in tests.
15. All generated code must include meaningful unit and integration tests; every story implementation must include tests for that story’s scope.
16. Update specs and README when behavior changes.

## Story-based implementation (per phase)

1. **Break down before coding:** Each phase must be broken into **implementation stories** before implementation on that phase begins (tracked in phase docs or a dedicated story list for the phase).
2. **Traceability:** Each story must reference the relevant phase spec sections (file paths or headings).
3. **Story content:** Each story must define **scope**, **acceptance criteria**, **test requirements**, and **out-of-scope** items.
4. **One story at a time:** Cursor implements only one story at a time.
5. **Gate the next story:** Do not start the next story until the current story is **tested and reviewed** (per project workflow).
6. **No opportunistic scope:** Do not implement future stories ahead of the active story.
7. **Scoped edits:** Do not modify unrelated areas unless the active story explicitly allows it.
8. **Status:** After implementation, update that story’s status in its artifact (e.g. draft / in progress / done).
9. **Tests:** Every story must ship tests that meet its test requirements (see core principle 15).
10. **Phase done:** A phase is complete only when all required stories are complete **and** phase acceptance criteria pass.

## Before coding, always produce

- Active story (or confirmation that story breakdown is the current task)
- Summary of requested work
- Affected files
- Proposed implementation plan aligned to the **single** active story
- Test plan
- Risks and assumptions

## After coding, always provide

- Story status update (artifact updated)
- What changed
- Tests added
- Commands to run
- Known limitations
- Whether the story acceptance criteria are satisfied; whether phase acceptance criteria are satisfied (if this story completes the phase)
